P. Scott Conti, president of Providence & Worcester Railroad Co., Worcester







Sunday
Jun 15, 2014 at 6:00 AM








Since 2005, P. Scott Conti has been president of the Providence & Worcester Railroad Company, a publicly traded company based in Worcester (with other headquarters in Cumberland, R.I. and Plainville, Conn.). He began his tenure in 1988 as an engineering manager, and worked his way up into other positions such as chief engineer and vice president of engineering by 1999. The Providence & Worcester Railroad Company is a short-line freight railroad operating in Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut and New York. Its operations involve transportation of a wide variety of commodities for its 140 customers including iron and steel products, processed foods, construction materials, chemicals, plastics and more. Last year, the company transported 34,402 carloads of freight.How has the company changed in the last couple of years to grow and adapt to market conditions?"The largest change we made in creating new opportunities is building access to multiple railroads. There are seven major Class I railroads in North America and the Providence & Worcester Railroad has access to four. We connect with CSX in Worcester, with Pan Am Southern and Norfolk Southern in Gardner and Canadian Pacific at Willimantic, Conn. Creating those interchanges allowed us to have better opportunities for traffic for our customers. It gives them more opportunities to bring freight to New England. P&W operates on a system of 516 miles to four states, so these connections allow access to our entire operating area. Another change has been in our employee base. The company for many years had employees that started in the '70s or early '80s and worked for 25 or 35 years. In the last four or five years, those employees retired, and we've hired new people to replace them that don't have the experience or institutional knowledge of the others — but are learning our business and bringing in innovative ideas and new opportunities to grow. They are being supervised to meet all the educational requirements and safety requirements of our system."P&W handles plastics, chemicals, lumber and a wide range of other products. Do you see an increase in particular areas and concurrently, are there items that you are handling less frequently?"Recently, the largest increase we've seen is in moving aggregates. And aggregates are (mined) in Connecticut on our property and they are used to create asphalt and concrete and construction materials. We haul those to other locations in Connecticut as well as New York City. There's a large construction market in NYC. That's an area where we've seen significant growth.  Areas where we've seen some decline mostly based on the energy market is dealing with coal. For years, we handled coal shipped into Providence, loaded on the dock and then moved to power plants in New Hampshire and Western Mass. And we connected with Pan Am Southern. One coal plant recently announced that it's closing this October. The other coal plant is on and off line based on the energy demands and the ability of the rate payers to pay. So when the gas-fired plants don't meet the demands or the pricing has an impact, the coal power will make up that demand or become that power demand based on pricing."Last year, the company's revenues grew by $3.3 million or 11.2 percent. How is that success continuing into 2014 and to what can it be attributed?"It's the aggregates. Currently, that's a market we can serve and having five loading points, not so much quarries, but sites where they load railcars on our property in Connecticut and being able to service the New York market has helped us to grow that commodity group. Also, we've seen intermodal pick up in the last two years and we expect it to continue. P&W handles international containers. They come in from all over the world via rail into Worcester and then are distributed into centers from that yard. It is a customs bonded facility and it handles the containers — and that's goods ranging from electronics, clothing and shoes to other manufactured items. That's a customer we've had since 1988, and it's different than the domestic containers that are handled. Our company has a diverse customer base with more than 140 customers, so we're very well rounded to be stable during economic changes here in New England. But it also gives us the opportunity to grow in different commodity groups and that's a big part of it as well."What do you think the public's biggest misconception is about your company and the service it provides?"There are a few, I'd say. We're a large railroad here in Worcester and a large landowner. We have a 516-mile system and we are highly visible, but we're not as big as the CSX Railroad. CSX is 21,000 miles. I think when people think of railroads, they think they are all quite large and we're not nearly as large as some of the bigger class ones. The Providence & Worcester Railroad also does not provide passenger service. We do have chartered excursion trains from time to time, and we work closely with the Blackstone Valley Tourism Council and the Mass Bay Rail Enthusiasts to operate trains on our system, but as far as running passengers from Worcester to Providence, that isn't in place just yet. It's possibly something that could happen in the future. Another misconception: We don't just operate freight from Worcester to Providence. We service a global market, and we're connected to the rail network throughout North America and we have multiple interchanges that I mentioned earlier. It's a big system and we're a piece of that."— Compiled by correspondent Susan Gonsalves













